---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="Manifesto | Tools for Sovereignty">
  <article class="container" style="padding-top: 4rem; padding-bottom: 6rem;">
    <header style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
      <p class="hero-date">Manifesto</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title">
        We're reclaiming<br />the web
      </h1>
    </header>

    <div class="manifesto-body">
      <section class="manifesto-section">
        <p>The internet is the most powerful tool humanity has ever built.</p>
        <p>
          It gave us connection, curiosity, and creativity at a scale we'd never seen before.
        </p>
        <p>But it wasn't meant to be like this.</p>
        <p>
          It started as a constellation of open protocols: email, RSS, HTTP, all stitched
          together with optimism and trust.
        </p>
        <p>
          That constellation wasn't a divine creation, it was built by people. Idealists.
          Cypherpunks, hackers, hippies. It was messy, it was cumbersome, but it was beautiful.
        </p>
        <p>Then, platforms took over. And with them came lock-in, surveillance, and silos.</p>
        <p>
          AI has an opportunity to steer us towards a better internet that inspires a
          renaissance of the freedom, trust, and privacy that made it humanity's greatest invention.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI, while revolutionary in scope, threatens to deepen the platform dominance:
          concentrating power in the hands of those with the most data and compute. Left
          unchecked, we risk flooding the internet with noise, losing the values that made
          it worth saving.
        </p>
        <p>
          We think it's time to liberate the web. Not backwards to the past, forward to
          something better.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="manifesto-section">
        <h2 class="manifesto-heading">The missing layer in AI</h2>
        <p>
          AI is incredible: a new substrate of software. Everything generated in real-time,
          tailored to you. But right now, it doesn't know who you are.
        </p>
        <p>
          We're building Mio because AI needs context: inference on top of your data,
          mapping who you are and what matters to you.
        </p>
        <p>
          Not just memorizing facts, but using intelligence: context, seeded from your own data.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="manifesto-section">
        <h2 class="manifesto-heading">Our bet</h2>
        <p>
          Most people are trying to solve personalization backwards: wait until the user does
          something, then use that information to make future answers better. Preferences are
          inferred slowly, often inaccurately, based on surface-level interaction data.
        </p>
        <p>We go upstream.</p>
        <p>
          We start with your existing data: the emails you've written, the docs you've edited,
          the signals you've already produced over decades of being online. The result?
          Personalization from the very first interaction, while preserving privacy.
        </p>
        <p>Step one: derive preferences directly from personal data.</p>
        <p>Step two: augment with usage.</p>
        <p>
          Step three: power everything with a shared context layer that moves across tools
          and models.
        </p>
        <p>Today, every app has its own algorithm. With Mio, every user brings their own.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="manifesto-section">
        <h2 class="manifesto-heading">Meet Mio</h2>
        <p>Mio is a tool for you to share your preferences across apps.</p>
        <p>
          Mio is your portable identity for the AI era. It's the gateway to an internet
          that works for you, is personalized to you and is controlled by you.
        </p>
        <p>Mio is:</p>
        <ul class="manifesto-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Private:</strong> We don't store your data. We don't
            even see it. It's your data, not ours.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Portable:</strong> No vendor lock-in. Your context
            goes where you go.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Simple:</strong> It just works. You get immediate
            personalization.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Developers can think of Mio as context as a service or automated context engineering.
          Mio isn't just another vector database provider, memory tool or MCP server; it's a
          compiler that translates user data into preferences for them to be consumed by AIs.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="manifesto-section">
        <h2 class="manifesto-heading">Why now</h2>
        <p>
          We're moving from algorithms that influence us to agents that act on our behalf.
        </p>
        <p>
          If we don't fix this now, we lock ourselves into a future where software acts on
          your behalf, but not in your interest.
        </p>
        <p>
          The internet's substrate is shifting. The cost of generating personalized content
          is approaching zero. For the first time, it's possible to build systems that are
          tailored to the individual and controlled by the individual.
        </p>
        <p>AI makes everything personal. Programmable cryptography makes everything portable.</p>
        <p>
          Together, they crack open the platform monopoly, and make space for new giants to
          emerge. We're already seeing it, from your code-editor to note-taker and beyond.
          This is the moment. We can build something better: private, portable, human-first.
        </p>
        <p>
          That's why we're building Mio: to carry forward the values the internet was meant
          to have, in tools built for today.
        </p>
        <p>
          This isn't just a manifesto, it's a roadmap. In the next few months, we're shipping
          the best context tool with:
        </p>
        <ul class="manifesto-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Portability by default:</strong> your context moves
            seamlessly across apps.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Day-one personalization:</strong> we derive preferences
            from your data, so apps feel tailored from the start.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Two-way integration:</strong> apps that read and write
            to Mio.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>

    <div style="border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); margin-top: 4rem; padding-top: 2rem;">
      <a href="/" class="back-link">
        &larr; Back to the maze
      </a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
